title: For Sale:  1903 Springfield made 1917 for World War One
postcontent:
Up for sale I have a Springfield 1903 bolt action rifle. It is in overall good condition. This is a low number 1903 that has had a hatcher hole added indicating possible USMC use. This is a low numbered receiver, considered by some to be non shooters. From what Ive read online the Marines continued to use low numbered rifles all the way through ww2. This was made in 1917 best I can tell. Finish is mostly patina. The barrel appears to be an Avis dated 10-18. Marking is very faint. I would rate the bore as fair, some light corrosion and looks frosty over all. Not a sewer pipe by any means. The muzzle wear is just over a 2. The stock has been nicely refinished and there is some shine to it. There is a small crack behind the receiver tang. This is some light old pitting on some parts of the receiver. It is not very noticable. Looks like its been there a long time. No import marks. Please feel free to ask any questions.
FTF on the south side of Indy. Will need to see an Indiana DL, no info will be recorded. 
Will trade plus cash for a nice Garand or M1 carbine.

Daniel Defense’s new caliber option, the 300 Blackout, was originally designed to give the shooter a 30 caliber projectile which could be fired out of the AR platform without an increase in magazine size while still utilizing a standard bolt. The 300 Blackout is 7.62x35mm which gives the shooter similar ballistic qualities as the .308 and the 7.62x39mm, the AK round, without having to give up the light weight 5.56mm/AR platform. title: For Sale:  .308 once fired military brass
location: West of OKC, Oklahoma City, Oklahoma
postcontent: What I have is some "once fired" .308/7.62 military brass from the militarys firing range. This brass has been lightly cleaned. It has NOT been deprimed/resized/trimmed to length or had the primer pocket crimp removed or has been processed in any other way. This is mostly Lake City brass with nato headstamp. However, other military headstamps may be included. I've had lots of questions over the last 6 months or so from new reloaders. This is guranteed once fired brass. Commercial mixed headstamp brass may have some rounds that have only been fired once. But will also include rounds that have been fired twice or multiple times. The amount of times availalbe to reload commercial brass are less than with once fired military brass. All reloading manuals reccomend sorting all mixed headstamp brass seperately. One of the reasons for this is each manufacturer's brass may have ever so slight different dimenions from one another and may process differently from other rounds from other manufacturers. Military brass is much more uniform and made to mil spec's. So be aware when purchasing cheaper commercial mixed headstamp brass. I'm asking .19 cents per round.

The SIX8™ weapons are short-stroke, gas-piston operated rifles chambered in the 6.8x43mm SPC cartridge. This cartridge was developed as part of the Enhanced Rifle Cartridge Program in which U.S. Special Operations soldiers, as well as armorers and other technicians from the U.S. Army Marksmanship Unit, played a major role. Its primary purpose was to address the deficiencies in terminal performance seen with the 5.56x45mm NATO cartridge, while allowing the soldier to carry the same number of rounds with minimal weight penalty. It succeeds in doing so because it uses a heavier bullet with excellent accuracy, which delivers more energy across all effective ranges.

Until now, a major drawback of using the 6.8 cartridge in an M4 style weapon has been the lack of reliable magazines. So, when we designed the SIX8™ family of weapons, we started with the magazine. Partnering with Magpul®, the leader in polymer magazine engineering, we designed the first polymer 6.8 magazine. Building upon the magazine, we designed the SIX8™ platform for maximum reliability and improved ergonomics. The upper and lower receivers are designed to accommodate the slightly larger polymer magazine and to perfect the feed geometry for the 6.8 cartridge. In addition, we have prompted Federal Ammunition to develop new lines of affordably priced, high performance 6.8 ammunition for commercial, law enforcement and military applications.

As with the IC family, the weapons in the new SIX8™ family are fully ambidextrous and equally suited to right- or left-handed operators. The SIX8™ rifles are based on the familiar Stoner M4/AR15/M16 architecture, but they have been optimized specifically for use with the 6.8 cartridge.

The new SIX8™ family combines the ultimate in ergonomic user-friendly rifles with the outstanding mid-range 6.8 cartridge.
